                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270913-309-off1720 t18270913-309-cd1721"></join>, 7 dwts. and 17 grs. of gold, value 20s.
            </rs>, the goods of 
               <persName id="t18270913-309-victim2344" type="victimName">
                  Francis 
                  Carpentier
               <interp inst="t18270913-309-victim2344" type="surname" value="Carpentier"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-309-victim2344" type="given" value="Francis"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-309-victim2344" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270913-309-off1720 t18270913-309-victim2344"></join>
                  </persName>
            , his master.</p>
               <p>FRANCIS CARPENTIER. I am a <rs id="t18270913-309-viclabel1722" type="occupation">goldsmith</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270913-309-victim2344 t18270913-309-viclabel1722"></join>, and live in Clerkenwell - the prisoner was in my employ. On the 13th of September he came to dinner as usual, but did not return to work - I found him in custody on Saturday. Mr. Simons produced some gold, which I compared with part of a diamond ring - they appeared to be the same; here is a piece which corresponds with it.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PRENDERGAST. Q. Was this standard gold? A. No, but it is jeweller's gold.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-309-person2345">
                  JOHN 
                  JAMES SIMONS
               <interp inst="t18270913-309-person2345" type="surname" value="JAMES SIMONS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-309-person2345" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-309-person2345" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a jeweller, and live on Clerkenwell-green - I saw the prisoner at my house on Thursday afternoon - he put these pieces of gold into the scale, and asked me to buy them. I asked where he got them; he said his mother gave it to him, that his name was William Smith, of Barbican-court, and that he worked at a rule makers; I said it had come from a goldsmith's, and if he did not tell me who his master was, I would give him in charge; he said he worked for no master - I then took him to the officer.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-309-person2346">
                  JAMES 
                  WALBANCK
               <interp inst="t18270913-309-person2346" type="surname" value="WALBANCK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-309-person2346" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-309-person2346" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am in the prosecutor's employ, and know this gold - I gave the prisoner part of it to work.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-309-person2347">
